Explanation

Use dot (.) operator

Example
printf("Roll: %d\n", s1.roll);
printf("Name: %s\n", s1.name);
printf("Marks: %.2f\n", s1.marks);

13. File Handling in C-

Question13- Explain the importance of file handling in C. Discuss how to performfile
operations like opening, closing, reading, and writing files.
Answer-
Introduction

In C, file handling allows storing data permanently in files instead of losing it when the program ends. It helps in saving, retrieving, and managing data efficiently.

Importance of File Handling
1. Permanent Data Storage

Stores data even after program execution ends

2. Data Management

Helps in handling large amounts of data

3. Reusability of Data

Data can be reused without re-entering

4. Efficient Processing

Makes reading and writing data faster and organized

Basic File Operations
1. Opening a File
Syntax
FILE *fp;
fp = fopen("filename.txt", "mode");
Modes

"r" → Read

"w" → Write (overwrite)

"a" → Append

2. Writing to a File
Example
#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
    FILE *fp;
    fp = fopen("data.txt", "w");

    fprintf(fp, "Hello, File Handling!");

    fclose(fp);
    return 0;
}
3. Reading from a File
Example
#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
    FILE *fp;
    char text[100];

    fp = fopen("data.txt", "r");

    fgets(text, 100, fp);
    printf("%s", text);

    fclose(fp);
    return 0;
}
4. Closing a File
Syntax
fclose(fp);
